				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tistical test</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, <b>one-way analysis of variance</b> (or <b>one-way ANO=
VA</b>) is a technique to compare whether two or more samples' means are si=
gnificantly different (using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"F distribution">F distributio=
n</a>). This <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_variance"=
 title=3D"Analysis of variance">analysis of variance</a> technique requires=
 a numeric <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependent_and_independe=
nt_variables" title=3D"Dependent and independent variables">response</a> va=
riable "Y" and a single explanatory variable "X", hence "one-way".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Howell_2002_324=E2=80=93325_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis_of_variance#cite_note-Ho=
well_2002_324%E2%80%93325-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_variance" t=
itle=3D"Analysis of variance">ANOVA</a> tests the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis<=
/a>, which states that samples in all groups are drawn from populations wit=
h the same mean values.  To do this, two estimates are made of the populati=
on variance.  These estimates rely on various assumptions (<a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis_of_variance#Assumptions">see belo=
w</a>). The ANOVA produces an F-statistic, the ratio of the variance calcul=
ated among the means to the variance within the samples. If the group means=
 are drawn from populations with the same mean values, the variance between=
 the group means should be lower than the variance of the samples, followin=
g the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=
=3D"Central limit theorem">central limit theorem</a>. A higher ratio theref=
ore implies that the samples were drawn from populations with different mea=
n values.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Howell_2002_324=E2=80=93325_1-1" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis_of_varianc=
e#cite_note-Howell_2002_324%E2%80%93325-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Typically, however, the one-way ANOVA is used to test for difference=
s among at least three groups, since the two-group case can be covered by a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-test" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"T-test">t-test</a> (Gosset, 1908). When there are only two means to c=
ompare, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-test" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"T-test">t-test</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/F-test" title=3D"F-test">F-test</a> are equivalent; the relation =
between ANOVA and <i>t</i> is given by <i>F</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<i>t</i><sup>=
2</sup>. An extension of one-way ANOVA is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Two-way_analysis_of_variance" title=3D"Two-way analysis of variance=
">two-way analysis of variance</a> that examines the influence of two diffe=
rent categorical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependent_and_ind=
ependent_variables" title=3D"Dependent and independent variables">independe=
nt variables</a> on one dependent variable.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Assumptions">Assumptions</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOne-way_analys=
is_of_variance&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: As=
sumptions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>The results of a one-way ANOVA can be considered reliable as long as the=
 following assumptions are met:
</p>
<ul><li>Response variable <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Errors_a=
nd_residuals_in_statistics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Errors and resid=
uals in statistics">residuals</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Normally_distributed" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Normally distribut=
ed">normally distributed</a> (or approximately normally distributed).</li>
<li>Variances of populations are equal.</li>
<li>Responses for a given group are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Independent_and_identically_distributed" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"I=
ndependent and identically distributed">independent and identically distrib=
uted</a> normal random variables (not a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Simple_random_sample" title=3D"Simple random sample">simple random sa=
mple</a> (SRS)).</li></ul>
<p>The major variants are: If data are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Ordinal_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ordinal scale">ordinal</=
a>, a non-parametric alternative to this test should be used such as <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kruskal%E2%80%93Wallis_one-way_analysis_=
of_variance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis one-way =
analysis of variance">Kruskal=E2=80=93Wallis one-way analysis of variance</=
a>. If the variances are not known to be equal, a generalization of 2-sampl=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welch%27s_t-test" title=3D"Welch=
's t-test">Welch's t-test</a> can be used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Welch1951_2-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_anal=
ysis_of_variance#cite_note-Welch1951-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Departures_from_population_=
normality">Departures from population normality</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOne-way_analysis_of_variance&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Departures from population =
normality"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>ANOVA is a relatively robust procedure with respect to violations of the=
 normality assumption.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kirk_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis_of_variance#cite_not=
e-Kirk-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The one-way ANOVA can be generalized to the factorial and multivaria=
te layouts, as well as to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anal=
ysis_of_covariance" title=3D"Analysis of covariance">analysis of covariance=
</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; whi=
te-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Pl=
ease_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"The text ne=
ar this tag may need clarification or removal of jargon. (September 2014)">=
clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>It is often stated in popular literature that none of these <i>F</i>=
-tests are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robust_statistics" titl=
e=3D"Robust statistics">robust</a> when there are severe violations of the =
assumption that each population follows the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distrib=
ution</a>, particularly for small alpha levels and unbalanced layouts.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/One-way_analysis_of_variance#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Furthermore, it is=
 also claimed that if the underlying assumption of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Homoscedasticity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Homosceda=
sticity">homoscedasticity</a> is violated, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Type_I_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Type I error">Typ=
e I error</a> properties degenerate much more severely.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_ana=
lysis_of_variance#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>However, this is a misconception, based on work done in the 1950s an=
d earlier.  The first comprehensive investigation of the issue by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method" title=3D"Monte Carlo =
method">Monte Carlo</a> simulation was Donaldson (1966).<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_an=
alysis_of_variance#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  He showed that under the usual =
departures (positive skew, unequal variances) "the <i>F</i>-test is conserv=
ative", and so it is less likely than it should be to find that a variable =
is significant.  However, as either the sample size or the number of cells =
increases, "the power curves seem to converge to that based on the normal d=
istribution". Tiku (1971) found that "the non-normal theory power of <i>F</=
i> is found to differ from the normal theory power by a correction term whi=
ch decreases sharply with increasing sample size."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis=
_of_variance#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  The problem of non-normality, especia=
lly in large samples, is far less serious than popular articles would sugge=
st.
</p><p>The current view is that "Monte-Carlo studies were used extensively =
with normal distribution-based tests to determine how sensitive they are to=
 violations of the assumption of normal distribution of the analyzed variab=
les in the population. The general conclusion from these studies is that th=
e consequences of such violations are less severe than previously thought. =
Although these conclusions should not entirely discourage anyone from being=
 concerned about the normality assumption, they have increased the overall =
popularity of the distribution-dependent statistical tests in all areas of =
research."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis_of_variance#cite_note-8"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For nonparametric alternatives in the factorial layout, see Sawilows=
ky.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis_of_variance#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For more d=
iscussion see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ANOVA_on_ranks" titl=
e=3D"ANOVA on ranks">ANOVA on ranks</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"The_case_of_fixed_effects,_=
fully_randomized_experiment,_unbalanced_data"><span id=3D"The_case_of_fixed=
_effects.2C_fully_randomized_experiment.2C_unbalanced_data"></span>The case=
 of fixed effects, fully randomized experiment, unbalanced data</h2><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOne-way_analysis_of_var=
iance&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: The case of=
 fixed effects, fully randomized experiment, unbalanced data"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"The_model">The model</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOne-way_analysis_o=
f_variance&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: The mo=
del"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>The normal linear model describes treatment groups with probability=20
distributions which are identically bell-shaped (normal) curves with=20
different means.  Thus fitting the models requires only the means of=20
each treatment group and a variance calculation (an average variance=20
within the treatment groups is used).  Calculations of the means and=20
the variance are performed as part of the hypothesis test.
</p><p>The commonly used normal linear models for a completely=20
randomized experiment are:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_analysis_of_variance#cite_note-=
10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
