<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Analysis_summary">Analysis =
summary</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOne-=
way_analysis_of_variance&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Analysis summary"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The core ANOVA analysis consists of a series of calculations.  The=20
data is collected in tabular form. Then
</p>
<ul><li>Each treatment group is summarized by the number of experimental un=
its, two sums, a mean and a variance.  The treatment group summaries are co=
mbined to provide totals for the number of units and the sums. The grand me=
an and grand variance are computed from the grand sums. The treatment and g=
rand means are used in the model.</li>
<li>The three DFs and SSs are calculated from the summaries.  Then the MSs =
are calculated and a ratio determines F.</li>
<li>A computer typically determines a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/P-value" title=3D"P-value">p-value</a> from F which determines whether =
treatments produce significantly different results.  If the result is signi=
ficant, then the model provisionally has validity.</li></ul>
<p>If the experiment is balanced, all of the <span class=3D"mwe-math-elemen=
t mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-m=
athml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/=
Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle I_{j}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>I</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>j</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle I_{j}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/b7cb04680c2246f78082e43ec912f72afe7af266" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:1.933ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle I_{=
j}}"></span> terms are =20
equal so the SS equations simplify.
</p><p>In a more complex experiment, where the experimental units (or=20
environmental effects) are not homogeneous, row statistics are also=20
used in the analysis.  The model includes terms dependent on=20
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe=
-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xm=
lns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle i}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>i</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle i}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/add78d8608ad86e54951b8c8bd6c8d8416533d20" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:0.802ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle i}"=
></span>.  Determining the extra terms reduces the number of
degrees of freedom available.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Example">Example</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOne-way_analysis_of_va=
riance&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Example"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>Consider an experiment to study the effect of three different levels of =
a factor on a response (e.g. three levels of a fertilizer on plant growth).=
 If we had 6 observations for each level, we could write the outcome of the=
 experiment in a table like this, where <i>a</i><sub>1</sub>, <i>a</i><sub>=
2</sub>, and <i>a</i><sub>3</sub> are the three levels of the factor being =
studied.
</p>
<dl><dd><table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"width:15%; text-align:center;">

<tbody><tr>
<th><i>a</i><sub>1</sub>
</th>
<th><i>a</i><sub>2</sub>
</th>
<th><i>a</i><sub>3</sub>
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td>6
</td>
<td>8
</td>
<td>13
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>8
</td>
<td>12
</td>
<td>9
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>4
</td>
<td>9
</td>
<td>11
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>5
</td>
<td>11
</td>
<td>8
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>3
</td>
<td>6
</td>
<td>7
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td>4
</td>
<td>8
</td>
<td>12
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<p>The null hypothesis, denoted H<sub>0</sub>, for the overall <i>F</i>-tes=
t for this experiment would be that all three levels of the factor produce =
the same response, on average. To calculate the <i>F</i>-ratio:
</p><p><b>Step 1:</b> Calculate the mean within each group:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\begin{aligned}{\overline {Y}}_{1}&amp;=3D{\frac {1}{6}}\sum Y_{1i}=3D{\=
frac {6+8+4+5+3+4}{6}}=3D5\\{\overline {Y}}_{2}&amp;=3D{\frac {1}{6}}\sum Y=
_{2i}=3D{\frac {8+12+9+11+6+8}{6}}=3D9\\{\overline {Y}}_{3}&amp;=3D{\frac {=
1}{6}}\sum Y_{3i}=3D{\frac {13+9+11+8+7+12}{6}}=3D10\end{aligned}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
